'''Sujata Sadan''' is a theatre auditorium in [[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Auditoriums in Kolkata|url=http://www.mapofkolkata.com/entertainment-and-recreation/auditoriums.html|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref> The theatre auditorium is located at 107 Harish Mukherjee Road, [[Kolkata]] 700026.<ref>{{cite web|title=Minutes of APRIL-19&20 final.pdf (application/pdf Object)|url=http://indiaculture.nic.in/indiaculture/pdf/Minutes%20of%20APRIL-19&20%20final.pdf|pages=38}}</ref> Bengali theatre group like [[Swapnasandhani]] regularly perform in this auditorium.<ref>{{cite news|title=A rolling repertory Stage On & Off|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1061104/asp/calcutta/story_6958118.asp|publisher=Telegraph|accessdate=10 March 2012|location=Calcutta, India|date=4 November 2006}}</ref>
==Theatre== The theatre was named after Sujata Devi.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sujata Sadan|url=http://in.local.yahoo.com/kolkata/sujata-devi-smriti-sadan-44a5ba6e78dd099c1ca5d60cb76a0c58/|accessdate=10 March 2012}}</ref> The theatre is not as popular as other theatres in [[Kolkata]] like [[Sisir Mancha]], [[Girish Mancha]], Academy of fine arts. The one floor auditorium is comparatively small in size. But, it is said, the auditorium is very good for [[Intimate Theatre|Intimate theatre]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}}
==Selected plays== Here a list of selected plays staged in Sujata Sadan.
===Swapnasandhani plays=== {{Unreferenced section|date=March 2012}} *Ajke Aamar Chhuti *Bhalo Rakshosher Golpo *Bhoy *Birpurush *Bankubabur Bandhu *Dakghor *Darjiparar Marjinara *Hargaj *Malyadan
===Other theatre groups=== *Aandhare ekla by Chetana.<ref>{{cite web|title=Aandhare Ekela-Bengali Drama Review|url=http://calcuttatube.com/aandhare-ekela-bengali-drama-review/106154/|publisher=Calcutta Tube|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref> *Pragoitihasik by Gotraheen ([[Dumdum]])<ref>{{cite news|title=Timeout|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120218/jsp/calcutta/story_15150807.jsp|publisher=Telegraph | location=Calcutta, India|date=18 February 2012}}</ref> *Katha Manobi by Niva Arts.<ref>{{cite news|title=Timeout Jan 25|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110125/jsp/calcutta/story_13489286.jsp|publisher=Telegraph|accessdate=10 March 2012|location=Calcutta, India|date=25 January 2011}}</ref> *Aadim Aranya by Gandeeb Natyam.
